{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}} '''Stuart White''' is an [[Australia]]n educator and [[sustainability]] advocate. He is a professor and the Director of the Institute for Sustainable Futures at the [[University of Technology, Sydney]]. White has researched sustainability for more than twenty years, specialising in [[Least cost planning methodology|least cost planning]] for utilities and resource use efficiency. In 1998, White was a member of the NSW Task Force on Water Conservation, and in 2001 was a member of the Expert Panel on Environmental Flows for the Hawkesbury Nepean.<ref>[http://www.atn.edu.au/atnconference/docs/Stuart%20White.pdf Professor Stuart White] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719141417/http://atn.edu.au/atnconference/docs/Stuart%20White.pdf |date=19 July 2008 }} Institute for Sustainable Futures. University of Technology, Sydney.</ref><ref>[http://www.expertguide.com.au/!ProfessorStuartWhite!_3773.aspx Professor Stuart White] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080722051741/http://www.expertguide.com.au/!ProfessorStuartWhite!_3773.aspx |date=22 July 2008 }}</ref> He has written widely on sustainable futures<ref>[http://datasearch.uts.edu.au/isf/staff/details.cfm?StaffId=2309 Professor Stuart White: Publications] Institute for Sustainable Futures. University of Technology, Sydney.</ref> and is often quoted in the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=The nuclear power option - expensive, ineffective and unnecessary|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/Opinion/The-nuclear-power-option--expensive-ineffective-and-unnecessary/2005/06/12/1118514925517.html#|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=13 June 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Stuart|last2=Riedy|first2=Chris|title=A climate protection act must have priority|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/opinion/a-climate-protection-act-must-have-priority/2006/11/01/1162339917711.html|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2 November 2006}}</ref> White has criticised the building of [[desalination]] plants, citing their high operational costs and energy usage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Expert pours cold water on desal|url=http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/national/expert-pours-cold-water-on-desal/story-e6frfku9-1225796874513|newspaper=news.com.au|date=12 November 2009}}</ref>
